From acf5cf600bcb09e6ba0fc2cea395e3054b7b2013 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Liibaan Egal <liibaaneagle@gmail.com>
Date: Mon, 11 May 2026 14:20:43 -0500
Subject: [PATCH] RDMA/rxe: prototype local-access implicit ODP MR support

RXE rejects the implicit ODP registration form (addr == 0,
length == U64_MAX, IB_ACCESS_ON_DEMAND) because it only sets up
explicit ODP umems via ib_umem_odp_get(). The implicit branch was a
placeholder with a Never reach here comment, and no path created
child umems for SGE accesses on an implicit MR.

Wire the implicit registration case through ib_umem_odp_alloc_implicit()
and route the local SGE walker through per-chunk child umems.

Registration. rxe_odp_mr_init_implicit() rejects remote access bits up
front (-EOPNOTSUPP), allocates the empty parent umem via
ib_umem_odp_alloc_implicit(), initializes mr->implicit_children via
xa_init(), and skips rxe_odp_init_pages(): there are no pages to fault
at registration time.

Chunking. Implicit MRs split the address space into fixed-size chunks
defined by RXE_ODP_CHILD_SHIFT (21, i.e. 2 MiB). Each chunk is backed
by at most one child ib_umem_odp allocated on demand. 2 MiB matches
the typical THP size on common arches, so a chunk can be served by a
huge page where one is available.

SGE fault path. rxe_odp_umem_for_iova() returns the parent for
explicit MRs and rxe_odp_get_child() for implicit MRs. The child
lookup is xa_load -> ib_umem_odp_alloc_child -> xa_cmpxchg(GFP_KERNEL);
a racing insertion drops the loser's child. rxe_odp_chunk_len_at()
reports how many bytes of an access can be served by one umem; for
explicit MRs that is the full request, for implicit it is the bytes
remaining in the current chunk. rxe_odp_mr_copy() loops across chunks,
resolving + locking + copying + unlocking each child independently.
Explicit MRs run the loop exactly once and see identical behavior to
the pre-patch path.

Multiple disjoint ranges on the same implicit MR are kept as distinct
children in the xarray and coexist without thrashing.

Prefetch. rxe_odp_prefetch_one() uses the same chunk loop so an
implicit MR can be prefetched. Async prefetch walks per chunk under
short-held mutexes so a long range does not stall concurrent
invalidators.

Atomic, flush, and atomic-write paths reject implicit MRs at the top
of each helper. These walk mr->umem->pfn_list directly which is empty
for an implicit parent; extending them is not in scope and rejecting
keeps the public claim aligned with what is verified.

Lifetime. rxe_mr_cleanup walks mr->implicit_children with xa_for_each
and ib_umem_odp_release()s each child before ib_umem_release() on the
parent, so each child's mmu_interval_notifier tears down while the
parent's per_mm is still alive. The xarray is xa_destroy()ed
afterwards.

The general_caps advertisement is extended with IB_ODP_SUPPORT_IMPLICIT
so userspace can probe support via ibv_query_device. Per-transport
caps are unchanged: they describe RC/UD behavior on explicit ODP MRs
and remain accurate for that path.

Limitations. The xarray grows monotonically per MR: a child is not
reclaimed until MR destroy. Long-lived MRs that touch a sparse
address space would accumulate children. A reclaim mechanism is the
natural next chunk of work.

Verified on Linux 6.17 (arm64, Soft-RoCE over loopback):
- five-case registration accept/reject matrix passes
- single-chunk 64 KiB RDMA WRITE through an implicit lkey delivers
- two-chunk multi test (two 1 MiB WRITEs from buffers in different
  2 MiB chunks of one implicit MR) delivers, exercising the xarray
- cross-chunk single-SGE test (128 KiB WRITE spanning a 2 MiB
  boundary) delivers, exercising the chunked copy loop

This is a prototype, not an upstream submission. See CLAIMS.md in the
companion rxe-implicit-odp repository for the exact scope boundary.

Signed-off-by: Liibaan Egal <liibaaneagle@gmail.com>
